Radcliffe's commitment

00:02:06.790 --> 00:02:11.350
to the integration of art
with other fields of study.

00:02:11.350 --> 00:02:15.340
Jeremy holds a PhD in history
from Columbia University,

00:02:15.340 --> 00:02:18.370
and he has taught at
Brandeis University.

00:02:18.370 --> 00:02:22.750
His scholarship focuses on
music and public memory.

00:02:22.750 --> 00:02:26.200
His critical essays have
appeared in many publications,

00:02:26.200 --> 00:02:29.530
including the New Yorker,
the Nation, the New Republic,

00:02:29.530 --> 00:02:31.750
Slate, and much more.

00:02:31.750 --> 00:02:34.360
Currently, he serves as
the chief classical music

00:02:34.360 --> 00:02:37.120
critic for the Boston Globe.

00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:41.110
To our great delight, Jeremy
is also a current Radcliffe

00:02:41.110 --> 00:02:42.270
Fellow.

00:02:42.270 --> 00:02:44.380
While he is here
with us this year,

00:02:44.380 --> 00:02:47.620
he is working on a book
about how music composed

00:02:47.620 --> 00:02:51.250
after World War II
captured and shaped

00:02:51.250 --> 00:02:54.310
collective memory
of epic events.

00:02:54.310 --> 00:02:57.880
Historians' attention to
the topic of cultural memory

00:02:57.880 --> 00:03:01.960
has grown in recent decades,
but it has focused mainly

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:06.520
on visual artifacts, like
paintings and statues that

00:03:06.520 --> 00:03:08.800
memorialize important events.

00:03:08.800 --> 00:03:11.350
Jeremy's work
turns our attention

00:03:11.350 --> 00:03:14.620
to musical
commemorations, and asks

00:03:14.620 --> 00:03:19.480
us to think about how the
past is venerated in sound.

00:03:19.480 --> 00:03:23.290
He'll be speaking to us
about that project today.

00:03:23.290 --> 00:03:25.690
But that is only
one of the projects

00:03:25.690 --> 00:03:27.770
that Jeremy has underway.

00:03:27.770 --> 00:03:30.820
He is also preparing
a book manuscript

00:03:30.820 --> 00:03:36.070
about the composition and public
reception of a 1947 cantata

00:03:36.070 --> 00:03:39.040
entitled, "A Survivor
from Warsaw,"

00:03:39.040 --> 00:03:41.800
which was the first
major musical memorial

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:43.420
to the Holocaust.

00:03:43.420 --> 00:03:46.520
That book grows out of
Jeremy's doctoral dissertation,

00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:49.420
which was entitled "The
Emancipation of Memory--

00:03:49.420 --> 00:03:51.250
Arnold Schoenberg
and the Creation

00:03:51.250 --> 00:03:54.760
of a Survivor from Warsaw,"
which won the Salo and Jeanette

00:03:54.760 --> 00:03:57.610
Baron Prize for the
best Columbia University

00:03:57.610 --> 00:04:01.390
dissertation in Jewish studies
defended over the previous five

00:04:01.390 --> 00:04:02.380
years.

00:04:02.380 --> 00:04:05.530
It combines biographical
study of the composer

00:04:05.530 --> 00:04:09.400
with a cultural and intellectual
history of classical music

00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:11.830
in the wake of epic tragedy.

00:04:11.830 --> 00:04:15.460
The Baron Prize Award Committee
praised Jeremy's dissertation

00:04:15.460 --> 00:04:19.779
for its in-depth research, its
ambitious theoretical scope,

00:04:19.779 --> 00:04:22.360
and its elegant prose.

00:04:22.360 --> 00:04:26.710
That same elegance typifies
Jeremy's critical writings,

00:04:26.710 --> 00:04:29.920
whether a review of
a single concerto

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:33.940
or an essay on the life
work of a major composer.

00:04:33.940 --> 00:04:37.990
Two of Jeremy's commentaries,
one about a Beethoven sculpture

00:04:37.990 --> 00:04:42.460
at Boston's MFA, and another
about the cultural amnesia

00:04:42.460 --> 00:04:46.840
behind the sale of American
composer Charles Ives' home,

00:04:46.840 --> 00:04:50.830
have won awards for
excellence in music writing.

00:04:50.830 --> 00:04:54.280
Jeremy's critical essays
are lovely to read,

00:04:54.280 --> 00:04:56.860
but they are much
more than ornaments.

00:04:56.860 --> 00:04:59.890
They do important cultural work.

00:04:59.890 --> 00:05:03.990
Another award-winning critic
and essayist, Daniel Mendelsohn,

00:05:03.990 --> 00:05:08.080
distilled the task of a
critic down to this equation--

00:05:08.080 --> 00:05:12.910
"knowledge plus taste
equals meaningful judgment."

00:05:12.910 --> 00:05:15.100
He explained that
the key difference

00:05:15.100 --> 00:05:18.370
between stating an
opinion and offering

00:05:18.370 --> 00:05:23.260
a lucid, critical assessment
comes down, in large measure,

00:05:23.260 --> 00:05:25.060
to expertise.

00:05:25.060 --> 00:05:29.530
A commodity that may seem to be
under suspicion these days, but

00:05:29.530 --> 00:05:33.370
is a quality crucial to
the advancement of both art

00:05:33.370 --> 00:05:35.020
and knowledge.

00:05:35.020 --> 00:05:37.480
We might all have
personal reactions,

00:05:37.480 --> 00:05:40.900
positive or negative, to
a poem, to a painting,

00:05:40.900 --> 00:05:44.140
or to a piece of music,
but we do not all

00:05:44.140 --> 00:05:48.370
have deep knowledge of the
arts' cultural context,

00:05:48.370 --> 00:05:52.600
of its historical origins, or
its political connotations.

00:05:52.600 --> 00:05:56.620
Nor are we all fluent in
the grammar or vocabulary

00:05:56.620 --> 00:05:59.110
of every artistic medium.

00:05:59.110 --> 00:06:02.380
To understand the significance
of a particular chord,

00:06:02.380 --> 00:06:04.900
or a brush stroke,
we must understand

00:06:04.900 --> 00:06:08.590
the range of options
available to a composer,

00:06:08.590 --> 00:06:12.910
or the array of techniques
that a painter had available.

00:06:12.910 --> 00:06:16.420
For those insights, we
rely on good critics, who

00:06:16.420 --> 00:06:19.270
do have that expert knowledge.

00:06:19.270 --> 00:06:23.470
We all know the saying
that everyone's a critic,

00:06:23.470 --> 00:06:26.140
but the truth is that
good critics, who

00:06:26.140 --> 00:06:28.930
dedicate their training,
their expertise,

00:06:28.930 --> 00:06:31.270
and their authoritative
judgment to deepening

00:06:31.270 --> 00:06:34.030
the meaning of art, are rare.

00:06:34.030 --> 00:06:37.930
Jeremy's contemporary criticism
and his historical scholarship

00:06:37.930 --> 00:06:42.010
deepen each other, and they
both enrich the understanding

00:06:42.010 --> 00:06:44.830
of his many audiences--
from students

00:06:44.830 --> 00:06:49.450
in history classes to readers
of his insightful reviews.

00:06:49.450 --> 00:06:53.440
In his hands, cultural
history and music criticism

00:06:53.440 --> 00:06:56.260
become entryways to
better understanding

00:06:56.260 --> 00:06:58.540
of the past and the present.

00:06:58.540 --> 00:07:00.880
And that is why I am
so pleased to have

00:07:00.880 --> 00:07:05.200
Jeremy here at Radcliffe
this year, and with us today.

