00:08:24.270 --> 00:08:27.960
On June 19, 1947,
the New York Times

00:08:27.960 --> 00:08:32.490
had some important
news to share.

00:08:32.490 --> 00:08:36.960
America would be getting its
very first Holocaust monument.

00:08:36.960 --> 00:08:40.230
The location was to be
on Manhattan's west side,

00:08:40.230 --> 00:08:44.540
on Riverside Avenue
at 84th Street.

00:08:44.540 --> 00:08:48.410
A few months later, on the
morning of October 19, 1947,

00:08:48.410 --> 00:08:51.860
some 15,000 people gathered
in the drizzling rain

00:08:51.860 --> 00:08:54.770
for the public dedication
of the future site.

00:08:54.770 --> 00:08:57.020
By that point, a
sculptor had been chosen,

00:08:57.020 --> 00:08:59.330
and a budget had been announced.

00:08:59.330 --> 00:09:01.820
The officials who gathered
there that morning

00:09:01.820 --> 00:09:05.810
to lay the cornerstone included
New York Mayor William O'Dwyer,

00:09:05.810 --> 00:09:09.140
Senator Irving Ives, and
many foreign dignitaries,

00:09:09.140 --> 00:09:14.000
whose speeches would be beamed
to Europe via shortwave radio.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:18.590
Indeed, a heavy symbolism
hung over the ceremony.

00:09:18.590 --> 00:09:20.510
Beneath the
cornerstone was placed

00:09:20.510 --> 00:09:24.230
a dedicatory Hebrew scroll,
written by the chief rabbi

00:09:24.230 --> 00:09:25.737
of Mandatory Palestine.

00:09:25.737 --> 00:09:27.320
It's a little hard
to make out, but we

00:09:27.320 --> 00:09:28.611
can see the scroll right there.

00:09:31.670 --> 00:09:35.300
It would take its place next to
a sampling of soil transported

00:09:35.300 --> 00:09:37.370
from the concentration
camp of Terezin,

00:09:37.370 --> 00:09:41.660
and presented by the foreign
minister of Czechoslovakia.

00:09:41.660 --> 00:09:44.480
100 survivors of
Buchenwald and Dachau

00:09:44.480 --> 00:09:48.160
were there for the
occasion, looking on

00:09:48.160 --> 00:09:50.450
as the Manhattan Borough
president compared

00:09:50.450 --> 00:09:53.360
the future memorial to
the Statue of Liberty.

00:09:53.360 --> 00:09:56.470
Albert Einstein couldn't
make it, but sent a message.

00:10:00.250 --> 00:10:02.260
The text of the
cornerstone that they laid

00:10:02.260 --> 00:10:04.780
that day reads as follows--

00:10:04.780 --> 00:10:06.940
"This is the site for
the American memorial

00:10:06.940 --> 00:10:09.850
to the heroes of the
Warsaw ghetto battle, April

00:10:09.850 --> 00:10:14.020
to May 1943, and to the 6
million Jews of Europe martyred

00:10:14.020 --> 00:10:16.720
in the cause of human liberty."

00:10:16.720 --> 00:10:20.050
A New York Times editorial
conferred its own benediction,

00:10:20.050 --> 00:10:23.830
stating, "May the monument
prove an eternal foundation

00:10:23.830 --> 00:10:26.770
for the spread of goodwill
and understanding in our land,

00:10:26.770 --> 00:10:30.930
and among all the
peoples of the earth."

00:10:30.930 --> 00:10:33.300
As it happened, the
foundation turned out

00:10:33.300 --> 00:10:37.770
to be far less eternal than the
Times editorial writers could

00:10:37.770 --> 00:10:40.110
have possibly imagined.

00:10:40.110 --> 00:10:42.780
One can still visit the
memorial's cornerstone today--

00:10:42.780 --> 00:10:45.450
this image is out there today--

00:10:45.450 --> 00:10:48.330
but you will find no
monument on this site.

00:10:48.330 --> 00:10:52.820
It was never built. The
project quickly became

00:10:52.820 --> 00:10:56.510
mired in controversies over the
aesthetic design, fundraising

00:10:56.510 --> 00:10:59.210
difficulties, and
bureaucratic delays.

00:10:59.210 --> 00:11:04.310
The site today remains haunted
by the memorial's absence.

00:11:04.310 --> 00:11:07.280
After all the good intentions
and vaunted symbolism,

00:11:07.280 --> 00:11:10.280
the space now stands
perhaps as a monument

00:11:10.280 --> 00:11:13.490
to memory's fickleness,
its contingency,

00:11:13.490 --> 00:11:16.670
its strange tendency
at times to court

00:11:16.670 --> 00:11:19.960
the very forces of oblivion
that it seeks to resist.

00:11:25.670 --> 00:11:28.430
The Holocaust has been
likened to an earthquake that

00:11:28.430 --> 00:11:32.630
shattered all the instruments
intended to record it.

00:11:32.630 --> 00:11:38.270
How, then, should an event like
this be commemorated in art?

00:11:38.270 --> 00:11:40.190
This theme-- the limits
of representation--

00:11:40.190 --> 00:11:43.070
is a well known one for the
first students of memory.

00:11:43.070 --> 00:11:45.920
Primo Levi wrote about
the inadequacy of language

00:11:45.920 --> 00:11:49.160
itself to describe the
horrors of camp life,

00:11:49.160 --> 00:11:52.070
and about the problem of
rationality being asked

00:11:52.070 --> 00:11:54.710
to serve as a guide
to the very places

00:11:54.710 --> 00:11:57.410
where it had been suspended.

00:11:57.410 --> 00:11:59.930
Claude Lanzmann, director
of the film, Shoah,

00:11:59.930 --> 00:12:01.640
has gone as far as
calling attempts

00:12:01.640 --> 00:12:04.400
to rationally, quote,
"understand," unquote,

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:07.340
the Holocaust an obscenity.

00:12:07.340 --> 00:12:10.040
Against this backdrop in
the early post-war years,

00:12:10.040 --> 00:12:14.420
as stone memorials went unbuilt,
we should perhaps not be

00:12:14.420 --> 00:12:16.760
particularly surprised
that it was, in fact,

00:12:16.760 --> 00:12:18.170
another art form--

00:12:18.170 --> 00:12:21.050
music-- that came to the
fore as one of the earliest

00:12:21.050 --> 00:12:23.510
mediums of commemoration.

00:12:23.510 --> 00:12:25.580
If you think about it,
music has a rare power

00:12:25.580 --> 00:12:28.970
to express strong emotion
without being delimited

00:12:28.970 --> 00:12:31.700
by the kind of
semantic specificity

00:12:31.700 --> 00:12:34.910
that is the province
of language alone.

00:12:34.910 --> 00:12:38.000
It also is not limited
by the visual clarity

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:41.360
that we associate with,
for instance, photography.

00:12:41.360 --> 00:12:43.640
Since the era of the
Romantics, various writers

00:12:43.640 --> 00:12:46.880
have found this aspect of
music to be a kind of catnip

00:12:46.880 --> 00:12:48.860
for the literary imagination.

00:12:48.860 --> 00:12:52.480
Thomas Mann, for one, described
this phenomenon as, quote,

00:12:52.480 --> 00:12:56.330
"the spoken unspokenness
given to music alone."

00:12:56.330 --> 00:12:59.180
Rilke wrote of music
as, quote, "the language

00:12:59.180 --> 00:13:01.940
where languages end."

00:13:01.940 --> 00:13:05.000
And so, let's clarify
some chronology.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.210
Before Mayor O'Dwyer announced
a memorial that would never

00:13:08.210 --> 00:13:10.820
arrive, before The
Diary of Anne Frank

00:13:10.820 --> 00:13:13.550
had been translated
into any other language,

00:13:13.550 --> 00:13:16.490
before the first book
of survivor testimony

00:13:16.490 --> 00:13:18.740
had been published
in the United States,

00:13:18.740 --> 00:13:22.760
before Alain Resnais' pioneering
documentary Night and Fog,

00:13:22.760 --> 00:13:26.180
and long before Adorno's
often quoted statement

00:13:26.180 --> 00:13:29.380
on the impossibility of
poetry after Auschwitz,

00:13:29.380 --> 00:13:33.940
the composer, Arnold
Schoenberg, who

00:13:33.940 --> 00:13:36.850
had spent the war years
in exile in Los Angeles,

00:13:36.850 --> 00:13:42.580
wrote a seven minute cantata
called A Survivor from Warsaw.

00:13:42.580 --> 00:13:45.400
It became one of the first
major works of commemorative art

00:13:45.400 --> 00:13:47.560
in any medium.

00:13:47.560 --> 00:13:50.680
We may think of sound as the
most slippery, evanescent,

00:13:50.680 --> 00:13:53.050
ever-vanishing medium of all.

00:13:53.050 --> 00:13:55.270
But in its way, as
these examples show,

00:13:55.270 --> 00:14:00.950
sonic memory can prove more
durable than that of stone.

00:14:00.950 --> 00:14:02.790
The connection between
music and memory

00:14:02.790 --> 00:14:06.750
might seem, at first blush,
to be so numerous and varied

00:14:06.750 --> 00:14:08.520
as to elude our grasp.

00:14:08.520 --> 00:14:10.620
The character, Swann, in
proofs from remembrance

00:14:10.620 --> 00:14:14.130
of things past, is greeted with
a flood of personal memories

00:14:14.130 --> 00:14:16.800
linked to a little
phrase in a violin sonata

00:14:16.800 --> 00:14:19.110
by the fictional
composer Vinteuil.

00:14:19.110 --> 00:14:22.710
And similarly, most listeners
can attest in their own lives

00:14:22.710 --> 00:14:25.850
to music's ability to
trigger personal reflections,

00:14:25.850 --> 00:14:29.910
upwellings of what Bergson
called memoire involontaire,

00:14:29.910 --> 00:14:31.330
involuntary memory.

00:14:31.330 --> 00:14:34.770
In fact, this linkage has
proven to be so robust

00:14:34.770 --> 00:14:37.200
that iPods with
personalized playlists

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:40.590
are now increasingly being used
in the treatment for patients

00:14:40.590 --> 00:14:44.970
with Alzheimer's and dementia,
as a way of excavating troves

00:14:44.970 --> 00:14:47.340
of personal memories
that have otherwise

00:14:47.340 --> 00:14:50.460
slipped beyond recall.

00:14:50.460 --> 00:14:53.610
The role of concert music as a
medium of civic commemoration

00:14:53.610 --> 00:14:55.770
may be equally accepted
on an intuitive level.

00:14:55.770 --> 00:14:59.490
Only four months after the
attack of September 11,

00:14:59.490 --> 00:15:01.020
the New York
Philharmonic contacted

00:15:01.020 --> 00:15:05.250
the American composer,
John Adams, to commission

00:15:05.250 --> 00:15:10.580
a memorial work, the
commission that became Adams'

00:15:10.580 --> 00:15:12.920
On the Transmigration of Souls.

00:15:12.920 --> 00:15:14.960
It was subsequently
premiered on the one year

00:15:14.960 --> 00:15:17.000
anniversary of the attacks.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.190
In his memoirs, Adams
describes reacting

00:15:19.190 --> 00:15:23.540
to the request with hesitation,
given the enormity of the task,

00:15:23.540 --> 00:15:25.460
but also with the
full understanding

00:15:25.460 --> 00:15:28.970
of music's critical role in
this manner, historically,

00:15:28.970 --> 00:15:29.940
and in the present.

00:15:29.940 --> 00:15:34.220
Someone, he realized,
needed to write this work.

00:15:34.220 --> 00:15:36.380
And yet, despite our
widely held notions

00:15:36.380 --> 00:15:38.930
of these supposedly natural
linkages between music

00:15:38.930 --> 00:15:41.090
and memory, music
and commemoration,

00:15:41.090 --> 00:15:43.490
the subject has received
surprisingly little attention

00:15:43.490 --> 00:15:44.600
from scholars.

00:15:44.600 --> 00:15:48.710
Indeed, despite its status
as a pioneering exemplar

00:15:48.710 --> 00:15:51.020
of the genre, you
won't find A Survivor

00:15:51.020 --> 00:15:53.330
from Warsaw even mentioned
in many histories

00:15:53.330 --> 00:15:54.590
of post-war memory.

00:15:54.590 --> 00:15:57.260
And across a wide range of
scholarship in this area,

00:15:57.260 --> 00:15:59.270
examining Holocaust
memory through the prism

00:15:59.270 --> 00:16:02.450
of literature, film,
architectural monuments,

00:16:02.450 --> 00:16:04.760
even pop culture,
one scarcely finds

00:16:04.760 --> 00:16:07.490
concert music mentioned at all.

00:16:07.490 --> 00:16:10.280
In our time today, I'd like to
pose a set of questions that

00:16:10.280 --> 00:16:12.740
has informed my project
this year at the Radcliffe

00:16:12.740 --> 00:16:15.470
institute, and I'd like
to at least gesture

00:16:15.470 --> 00:16:18.680
in the direction of some
preliminary answers.

00:16:18.680 --> 00:16:22.310
I'd also like to share with
you some musical examples.

00:16:22.310 --> 00:16:26.960
And along the way, I
will try to be addressing

00:16:26.960 --> 00:16:28.560
a series of questions--

00:16:28.560 --> 00:16:32.660
What is lost when we
fail to consider sound

00:16:32.660 --> 00:16:35.450
as a carrier of
meaning about the past?

00:16:35.450 --> 00:16:37.280
Why is music, in
fact, particularly

00:16:37.280 --> 00:16:39.590
effective as a medium
of cultural memory,

00:16:39.590 --> 00:16:43.100
capable of powerfully
conveying personal and national

00:16:43.100 --> 00:16:47.030
narratives about war,
rupture, and displacement?

00:16:47.030 --> 00:16:50.720
How do monuments in sound
do their work differently

00:16:50.720 --> 00:16:53.390
from their sibling
monuments in stone?

00:16:53.390 --> 00:16:59.025
And on an experiential,
sensorial level,

00:16:59.025 --> 00:17:02.060
how do oral and visual
encounters with memory art

00:17:02.060 --> 00:17:04.790
differ from each other,
that is, memory perceived

00:17:04.790 --> 00:17:06.740
through our ears
versus that which

00:17:06.740 --> 00:17:08.660
is perceived through our eyes?

00:17:08.660 --> 00:17:13.990
How, in short, has a wartime
past been inscribed in sound?

00:17:13.990 --> 00:17:15.890
And what does it
mean to cultivate

00:17:15.890 --> 00:17:18.650
new ways of hearing
these works precisely

00:17:18.650 --> 00:17:21.800
at our current moment, that
is, as the generation that

00:17:21.800 --> 00:17:24.290
lived through the reality
to which this music bears

00:17:24.290 --> 00:17:28.880
testament is itself
fading into history?

00:17:28.880 --> 00:17:31.550
So those are some questions to
keep in the back of our minds

00:17:31.550 --> 00:17:32.600
as we proceed.

00:17:32.600 --> 00:17:35.990
We may explore a few offshoots
and alleyways along the way.

00:17:35.990 --> 00:17:37.730
But that's OK as well.

00:17:37.730 --> 00:17:39.450
As a friend of
mine likes to say,

00:17:39.450 --> 00:17:42.007
digression is the
sunshine of narrative.

00:17:42.007 --> 00:17:44.442
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:46.390 --> 00:17:48.970
Arnold Schoenberg was born
into a Viennese Jewish family

00:17:48.970 --> 00:17:50.890
in 1874.

00:17:50.890 --> 00:17:55.060
He is, of course, both revered
and reviled to this day

00:17:55.060 --> 00:17:58.270
for his place as a forefather
of musical modernism,

00:17:58.270 --> 00:18:01.570
the composer, who, in his
words, emancipated dissonance,

00:18:01.570 --> 00:18:04.360
and, in so doing,
severed music's link

00:18:04.360 --> 00:18:06.640
with the system of
tonal organization

00:18:06.640 --> 00:18:10.900
that had governed the art
form since the Baroque era.

00:18:10.900 --> 00:18:13.720
And yet, years before his
invention of his signature

00:18:13.720 --> 00:18:17.420
twelve-tone method of
composition in 1921,

00:18:17.420 --> 00:18:20.050
Schoenberg had staked out
his own radical position

00:18:20.050 --> 00:18:23.440
on a subject perhaps even more
fundamental to music than its

00:18:23.440 --> 00:18:25.090
harmonic language--

00:18:25.090 --> 00:18:28.060
the ethical purpose of music.

00:18:28.060 --> 00:18:31.000
The art of the future,
he felt strongly,

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:33.130
should not strive
to be beautiful.

00:18:33.130 --> 00:18:35.690
It should strive to be true.

00:18:35.690 --> 00:18:38.680
"Art," he wrote in
1911, "is the cry

00:18:38.680 --> 00:18:42.640
of distress uttered by those
who experience firsthand

00:18:42.640 --> 00:18:45.730
the fate of mankind."

00:18:45.730 --> 00:18:48.430
In the early 1930s, Schoenberg
was among the very first

00:18:48.430 --> 00:18:50.290
German-speaking
artists to perceive

00:18:50.290 --> 00:18:53.020
the urgency of the threat
facing European Jews.

00:18:53.020 --> 00:18:56.710
He emigrated in 1933 and
settled in Los Angeles.

00:18:56.710 --> 00:18:59.470
After the war, which claimed
the lives of several family

00:18:59.470 --> 00:19:04.270
members, he composed his own
short, but explosive, cry

00:19:04.270 --> 00:19:07.750
of distress, his Survivor
from Warsaw, on a commission

00:19:07.750 --> 00:19:11.440
from the foundation of Serge
Koussevitzky, music director

00:19:11.440 --> 00:19:13.570
of the Boston Symphony.

00:19:13.570 --> 00:19:16.390
Koussevitzky was renowned for
championing the music of living

00:19:16.390 --> 00:19:18.340
composers, and he
gave Schoenberg

00:19:18.340 --> 00:19:21.850
enormous creative latitude as
to how the commission would

00:19:21.850 --> 00:19:23.140
be fulfilled.

00:19:23.140 --> 00:19:25.960
Interesting, nothing I ended
up finding in the archives

00:19:25.960 --> 00:19:28.990
indicates that
Koussevitzky had any idea

00:19:28.990 --> 00:19:31.120
that Schoenberg
planned to compose

00:19:31.120 --> 00:19:33.100
a memorial to the Holocaust.

00:19:33.100 --> 00:19:37.960
We can imagine his surprise upon
receiving this bracing score.

00:19:37.960 --> 00:19:39.520
He was a conductor,
after all, who

00:19:39.520 --> 00:19:43.840
had a very different vision
for the role of music

00:19:43.840 --> 00:19:46.390
in the era of post-war
reconstruction.

00:19:46.390 --> 00:19:48.310
He spelled out that
vision in a speech

00:19:48.310 --> 00:19:51.820
to the first class of students
who returned to Tanglewood,

00:19:51.820 --> 00:19:53.650
once it reopened after the war.

00:19:58.470 --> 00:20:00.890
He told the students,
"In light of music,

00:20:00.890 --> 00:20:03.800
the soul beholds the
good and the beautiful,

00:20:03.800 --> 00:20:07.730
the heart awakens to faith in
man and in his better future.

00:20:07.730 --> 00:20:09.650
If you deprive men of music--

00:20:09.650 --> 00:20:11.930
just as they were deprived
of honor, dignity,

00:20:11.930 --> 00:20:14.840
human rights, conscience,
faith, and freedom--

00:20:14.840 --> 00:20:17.060
you will witness the
decline of the world

00:20:17.060 --> 00:20:19.880
to a state of brutality
and barbarism.

00:20:19.880 --> 00:20:23.390
Music alone can still
tame the beast in man--

00:20:23.390 --> 00:20:27.530
it is our comfort and our hope."

00:20:27.530 --> 00:20:29.930
This is, of course,
quite far removed

00:20:29.930 --> 00:20:35.870
from any notion of music as
the soul's cry of distress.

00:20:35.870 --> 00:20:38.090
And A Survivor from
Warsaw, one might say,

00:20:38.090 --> 00:20:43.700
does not tame any beast, but it
rather depicts them in its art.

00:20:43.700 --> 00:20:45.590
As we'll hear shortly,
the piece itself

00:20:45.590 --> 00:20:49.100
is a narrated scene that takes
place in a concentration camp.

00:20:49.100 --> 00:20:52.460
This work would not be
Koussevitzky's avenue

00:20:52.460 --> 00:20:56.270
to moral and
aesthetic redemption.

00:20:56.270 --> 00:20:58.760
It's in those terms that
I interpret Koussevitzky's

00:20:58.760 --> 00:21:02.990
otherwise mysterious decision
to tacitly decline the chance

00:21:02.990 --> 00:21:05.341
to give the work's world
premiere with the Boston

00:21:05.341 --> 00:21:05.840
Symphony.

00:21:09.920 --> 00:21:12.230
Almost all of his
other commissions

00:21:12.230 --> 00:21:15.110
received the BSO's
red carpet treatment.

00:21:15.110 --> 00:21:17.900
Not this one.

00:21:17.900 --> 00:21:20.420
Instead, I think because
Survivor from Warsaw

00:21:20.420 --> 00:21:23.780
was so far ahead of the
curve of public Holocaust

00:21:23.780 --> 00:21:25.820
memory in this
country, the score

00:21:25.820 --> 00:21:28.070
was pushed to what
were then the margins

00:21:28.070 --> 00:21:30.010
of American musical life.

00:21:30.010 --> 00:21:32.840
In what is surely one of
the strangest premieres

00:21:32.840 --> 00:21:34.940
of a major work
in music history,

00:21:34.940 --> 00:21:38.030
this piece was unveiled
in a university gymnasium

00:21:38.030 --> 00:21:41.930
in Albuquerque, New
Mexico, in 1948,

00:21:41.930 --> 00:21:45.620
with an Austrian conductor
named Kurt Frederick leading

00:21:45.620 --> 00:21:50.350
an amateur chorus and
an amateur orchestra.

00:21:50.350 --> 00:21:54.460
The performers included cowboys,
florists, assorted students,

00:21:54.460 --> 00:21:56.320
and railroad engineers.

00:21:56.320 --> 00:21:59.320
The narrator was the head
of the university chemistry

00:21:59.320 --> 00:22:01.050
department.

00:22:01.050 --> 00:22:03.770
Here is a copy of the program.

00:22:03.770 --> 00:22:06.280
The national press
sent correspondence.

00:22:06.280 --> 00:22:08.320
The New York Times
ran a headline--

00:22:08.320 --> 00:22:11.500
"Schoenberg in Albuquerque"--
sounding more like the set up

00:22:11.500 --> 00:22:14.440
for a joke about two
things that go together

00:22:14.440 --> 00:22:18.450
about as well as, say, a
Sachertorte and a campfire.

00:22:21.340 --> 00:22:23.110
But from all accounts,
the work seems

00:22:23.110 --> 00:22:25.780
to have been an unqualified
success at its premiere.

00:22:25.780 --> 00:22:27.820
The piece had to
be repeated twice.

00:22:27.820 --> 00:22:29.800
Time magazine
reported that applause

00:22:29.800 --> 00:22:31.320
thundered in the auditorium.

00:22:31.320 --> 00:22:32.920
Schoenberg was
not healthy enough

00:22:32.920 --> 00:22:35.560
to travel for the performance,
but Kurt Frederick, just

00:22:35.560 --> 00:22:37.840
after midnight on the
night of the premiere,

00:22:37.840 --> 00:22:41.860
dashed off this telegram to
Schoenberg in Los Angeles--

00:22:41.860 --> 00:22:44.380
"Survivor from Warsaw
made tremendous impression

00:22:44.380 --> 00:22:46.270
on the performers and audience.

00:22:46.270 --> 00:22:48.430
Thank you for the
great honor of allowing

00:22:48.430 --> 00:22:51.850
us to perform this work."

00:22:51.850 --> 00:22:53.800
In its early years, the
piece earned champions

00:22:53.800 --> 00:22:57.110
well beyond the good burghers
of Albuquerque, New Mexico,

00:22:57.110 --> 00:23:00.280
including one listener who
championed it precisely

00:23:00.280 --> 00:23:02.140
for the same reasons
that Koussevitzky

00:23:02.140 --> 00:23:04.060
appears to have ignored it.

00:23:04.060 --> 00:23:06.850
I'm speaking of the philosopher,
critic, and musical thinker,

00:23:06.850 --> 00:23:11.230
Theodor Adorno, who wrote
that, "In Survivor, perhaps

00:23:11.230 --> 00:23:14.230
for the first time,
culture and barbarism

00:23:14.230 --> 00:23:17.720
were not shown as
naively opposing forces,

00:23:17.720 --> 00:23:19.630
but rather wrenched
into the frame

00:23:19.630 --> 00:23:22.450
of a single explosive
work of art."

00:23:22.450 --> 00:23:24.610
in Adorno's reading,
the work's incorporation

00:23:24.610 --> 00:23:27.610
of horror and suffering
was exactly what

00:23:27.610 --> 00:23:30.250
provided its truth content.

00:23:30.250 --> 00:23:33.320
Here is a fuller
quote from Adorno--

00:23:33.320 --> 00:23:35.530
"The effect of the
Survivor from Warsaw

00:23:35.530 --> 00:23:38.230
is no less powerful--
a companion piece

00:23:38.230 --> 00:23:40.720
to Picasso's Guernica--
in which Schoenberg

00:23:40.720 --> 00:23:42.910
made the impossible
possible, standing up

00:23:42.910 --> 00:23:46.090
to the contemporary horror
in its most extreme form,

00:23:46.090 --> 00:23:48.850
the murder of the Jews, in art.

00:23:48.850 --> 00:23:51.850
If music is to escape from
the nullity that threatens it,

00:23:51.850 --> 00:23:53.740
the very loss of
its raison d'etre,

00:23:53.740 --> 00:23:57.670
then it can only hope to
do so if it accomplishes

00:23:57.670 --> 00:24:01.120
what Schoenberg accomplished
in the Survivor from Warsaw,

00:24:01.120 --> 00:24:04.900
that is, if it confronts the
utter negativity, the most

00:24:04.900 --> 00:24:08.770
extreme, by which the
entire complexion of reality

00:24:08.770 --> 00:24:12.170
is made manifest."

00:24:12.170 --> 00:24:14.610
To put his comment
in anecdotal form,

00:24:14.610 --> 00:24:17.220
I'll mention that, in a
different essay on Schoenberg,

00:24:17.220 --> 00:24:19.530
Adorno recalls the
memorable story

00:24:19.530 --> 00:24:24.300
about Picasso's famous
depiction of wartime slaughter.

00:24:24.300 --> 00:24:26.610
Gestapo officers were
said to have, one day,

00:24:26.610 --> 00:24:28.920
approached the great
painter near a photograph

00:24:28.920 --> 00:24:30.960
of his Guernica.

00:24:30.960 --> 00:24:33.540
"Did you do this?"
they asked him.

00:24:33.540 --> 00:24:36.200
"No," the painter
replied, "you did."

00:24:39.500 --> 00:24:41.084
Before playing A
Survivor from Warsaw,

00:24:41.084 --> 00:24:43.000
for those of you who
might not know the piece,

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:45.270
here is a quick overview
of what you'll be hearing.

00:24:45.270 --> 00:24:46.740
It lasts just seven minutes.

00:24:46.740 --> 00:24:50.420
It's scored for narrator and
orchestra and male chorus.

00:24:50.420 --> 00:24:52.220
After a brief
orchestral opening,

00:24:52.220 --> 00:24:55.130
the narrator recites a
text written by Schoenberg

00:24:55.130 --> 00:24:59.720
to be delivered in a hybrid
speech-song style known

00:24:59.720 --> 00:25:01.160
as Sprechstimme.

00:25:01.160 --> 00:25:03.590
This narrator, as we'll
hear, describes a scene

00:25:03.590 --> 00:25:06.380
he has witnessed in a
concentration camp involving

00:25:06.380 --> 00:25:09.440
the beating of prisoners and
their selection for the gas

00:25:09.440 --> 00:25:10.490
chamber.

00:25:10.490 --> 00:25:13.370
At the climax of his
story, the men's choir

00:25:13.370 --> 00:25:16.340
enters singing Schoenberg's
own setting of the Hebrew

00:25:16.340 --> 00:25:19.670
words of the Shema Yisrael
prayer, the central prayer

00:25:19.670 --> 00:25:22.130
of Judaism.

00:25:22.130 --> 00:25:25.700
And one the last word of caution
before we press play here

00:25:25.700 --> 00:25:27.860
for our musical example.

00:25:27.860 --> 00:25:30.350
Judgment of this
score's aesthetic merits

00:25:30.350 --> 00:25:33.680
has been all over the
map over the years, which

00:25:33.680 --> 00:25:36.440
is, in fact, a subject of an
entirely different lecture--

00:25:36.440 --> 00:25:38.510
how we should
think about judging

00:25:38.510 --> 00:25:43.940
these monuments in aesthetic
terms, or in other terms.

00:25:43.940 --> 00:25:46.880
But the piece has been
heralded as, quote,

00:25:46.880 --> 00:25:50.210
"the aesthetic and ethical
manifesto of our time,"

00:25:50.210 --> 00:25:51.470
unquote.

00:25:51.470 --> 00:25:53.180
That was from Luigi Nono.

00:25:53.180 --> 00:25:56.900
And it's also been derided
as, quote, "Hollywood kitsch."

00:25:56.900 --> 00:25:59.300
You can each judge
for yourself, though

00:25:59.300 --> 00:26:00.830
to the extent that
this is possible,

00:26:00.830 --> 00:26:04.460
I'd ask you to listen in a
spirit of oral generosity,

00:26:04.460 --> 00:26:08.270
and to remember, just as
historians like to caution us

00:26:08.270 --> 00:26:10.790
against back-shadowing,
which is viewing

00:26:10.790 --> 00:26:13.340
the past through the
prism of the present,

00:26:13.340 --> 00:26:15.830
I think we'd be wise to
guard against the equivalent

00:26:15.830 --> 00:26:19.070
phenomenon in the domains
of memory and listening.

00:26:19.070 --> 00:26:21.020
In other words,
try to keep in mind

00:26:21.020 --> 00:26:24.890
that this was written in
1947, before, as we've said,

00:26:24.890 --> 00:26:28.815
just about any other artifact
of Holocaust you might think of.

00:26:28.815 --> 00:26:30.440
If you'd like, you
can picture yourself

00:26:30.440 --> 00:26:35.360
sitting in the Carlisle
Gymnasium of the University

00:26:35.360 --> 00:26:39.320
of Albuquerque on November
4, 1948, the night

00:26:39.320 --> 00:26:42.350
that this music
was actually new.

00:26:42.350 --> 00:26:45.920
I'll put the text up here
for us to follow as we read.

00:26:45.920 --> 00:26:50.154
And here is the piece that
they heard that night.

00:26:50.154 --> 00:27:32.399
[MUSIC - ARNOLD SCHOENBERG, "A
 SURVIVOR FROM WARSAW"]

00:27:32.399 --> 00:27:35.970
- I cannot remember everything.

00:27:35.970 --> 00:27:39.612
I must have been unconscious
most of the time.

00:27:43.390 --> 00:27:49.820
I remember only the
grandiose moment

00:27:49.820 --> 00:27:57.140
when they all started to
sing, as if prearranged

00:27:57.140 --> 00:28:00.890
the old prayer
they had neglected

00:28:00.890 --> 00:28:06.000
for so many years,
the forgotten creed.

00:28:13.125 --> 00:28:17.100
But I have no recollection
how I got underground

00:28:17.100 --> 00:28:24.924
to live in the sewers of
Warsaw so long a time.

00:28:24.924 --> 00:28:27.875
The day began as usual--

00:28:27.875 --> 00:28:31.763
Reveille when it still was dark.

00:28:31.763 --> 00:28:33.210
"Get out!"

00:28:33.210 --> 00:28:35.390
Whether you slept,
or whether worries

00:28:35.390 --> 00:28:37.642
kept you awake the whole night.

00:28:37.642 --> 00:28:41.240
You had been separated from
your children, from your wife,

00:28:41.240 --> 00:28:42.224
from your parents.

00:28:42.224 --> 00:28:44.192
You don't know what
happened to them.

00:28:44.192 --> 00:28:46.160
How could you sleep?

00:28:56.492 --> 00:28:58.431
The trumpets again--

00:28:58.431 --> 00:28:58.930
"Get out!

00:28:58.930 --> 00:29:02.820
The sergeant will be furious!"

00:29:02.820 --> 00:29:07.650
They came out, some very
slowly-- the old ones,

00:29:07.650 --> 00:29:10.990
the sick ones, some
with nervous agility.

00:29:10.990 --> 00:29:12.950
They fear the sergeant.

00:29:12.950 --> 00:29:15.360
They hurry as much as they can.

00:29:15.360 --> 00:29:16.130
In vain!

00:29:19.088 --> 00:29:23.032
Much too much noise,
much too much commotion!

00:29:23.032 --> 00:29:24.018
And not fast enough!

00:29:24.018 --> 00:29:25.497
The Feldwebel shouts--

00:29:25.497 --> 00:29:26.483
"Achtung!

00:29:26.483 --> 00:29:27.469
Stilljestanden!

00:29:27.469 --> 00:29:28.455
Na wird's mal!

00:29:28.455 --> 00:29:31.906
Oder soll ich mit dem
Jewehrkolben nachhelfen?

00:29:31.906 --> 00:29:36.740
Na jut-- wenn ihrs
durchaus haben wollt!"

00:29:36.740 --> 00:29:38.810
The sergeant and
his subordinates

00:29:38.810 --> 00:29:41.753
hit everyone-- young
or old, strong or sick,

00:29:41.753 --> 00:29:43.874
guilty or innocent.

00:29:43.874 --> 00:29:49.290
It was painful to hear
them groaning and moaning.

00:29:53.622 --> 00:29:59.195
I heard it though I had
been hit very hard, so hard

00:29:59.195 --> 00:30:01.620
that I couldn't
help falling down.

00:30:06.470 --> 00:30:09.464
We all on the ground
who couldn't stand up

00:30:09.464 --> 00:30:11.944
were then beaten over the head.

00:30:29.800 --> 00:30:32.550
I must have been unconscious.

00:30:32.550 --> 00:30:36.080
The next thing I knew
was a soldier saying--

00:30:36.080 --> 00:30:40.526
"They are all dead!"

00:30:40.526 --> 00:30:45.375
Whereupon the sergeant ordered
leave to do away with us.

00:30:45.375 --> 00:30:54.124
There I lay aside
half conscious.

00:30:54.124 --> 00:31:00.578
It had become very still.

00:31:00.578 --> 00:31:03.013
Fear and pain.

00:31:05.935 --> 00:31:09.484
Then I heard the
sergeant shouting--

00:31:09.484 --> 00:31:11.770
"Achtung!"

00:31:11.770 --> 00:31:17.680
They started slowly
and irregularly--

00:31:17.680 --> 00:31:22.869
one, two, three, four.

00:31:22.869 --> 00:31:24.801
"Achtung!"

00:31:24.801 --> 00:31:28.591
the sergeant shouted again.

00:31:28.591 --> 00:31:30.052
"Rascher!

00:31:30.052 --> 00:31:32.487
Nochmals von vorn anfange!

00:31:32.487 --> 00:31:35.409
In einer Minute will ich wissen,
wieviele ich zur Gaskammer

00:31:35.409 --> 00:31:36.383
abliefere!

00:31:40.766 --> 00:31:41.740
Abzahlen!"

00:31:45.950 --> 00:31:51.174
They began again, first slowly--

00:31:51.174 --> 00:31:55.490
one, two, three, four.

00:31:55.490 --> 00:32:00.780
Became faster and
faster, so fast

00:32:00.780 --> 00:32:07.974
that they finally sounded like
a stampede of wild horses.

00:32:07.974 --> 00:32:11.966
And all of a sudden,
in the middle of it,

00:32:11.966 --> 00:32:16.457
they began singing
the Shema Yisrael.

00:32:16.457 --> 00:32:18.952
[MEN'S CHOIR IN
BACKGROUND SINGING

00:32:18.952 --> 00:34:06.390
"SHEMA YISRAEL"]

00:34:06.390 --> 00:34:11.250
- Philosophers of
music have written

00:34:11.250 --> 00:34:15.510
about an intriguing
enigma at the heart

00:34:15.510 --> 00:34:22.460
of the work of music, a kind
of ontological fuzziness.

00:34:22.460 --> 00:34:24.770
In the case of painting,
once the artist

00:34:24.770 --> 00:34:27.850
has finished her
creative activity,

00:34:27.850 --> 00:34:32.929
the painted canvas itself is
manifestly the work of art.

00:34:32.929 --> 00:34:37.969
But where, or alternatively,
when does the work of musical

00:34:37.969 --> 00:34:40.110
art reside?

00:34:40.110 --> 00:34:42.280
Is a score like this
one-- or let's say,

00:34:42.280 --> 00:34:45.989
is Beethoven's Ninth Symphony--

00:34:45.989 --> 00:34:48.771
is the piece itself to be found
in the score of Beethoven's

00:34:48.771 --> 00:34:49.270
Ninth?

00:34:49.270 --> 00:34:53.420
Is it located in a particular
performance of the symphony?

00:34:53.420 --> 00:34:56.949
In the average of many
performances over time?

00:34:56.949 --> 00:35:00.610
Or perhaps in some platonic
idealized version of the score

00:35:00.610 --> 00:35:03.670
that lives only in our minds?

00:35:03.670 --> 00:35:06.970
In short, a kind of
temporal ambiguity

00:35:06.970 --> 00:35:10.750
appears to be part of the
notated music tradition itself.

00:35:10.750 --> 00:35:12.610
A score is a blueprint--

00:35:12.610 --> 00:35:15.430
instructions for
realization at a later date.

00:35:15.430 --> 00:35:18.040
We might go further
still to suggest

00:35:18.040 --> 00:35:20.950
that the active musical
performance of any score

00:35:20.950 --> 00:35:26.520
exposes listeners to a unique
kind of enlarged temporality,

00:35:26.520 --> 00:35:29.800
a bridge between the present
tense of the listener

00:35:29.800 --> 00:35:35.050
experiencing the performance and
the present tense of the music

00:35:35.050 --> 00:35:38.650
at the time of its composition.

00:35:38.650 --> 00:35:41.390
In this sense, we might say
that a musical monument carries

00:35:41.390 --> 00:35:44.300
in it a memory of
its own history,

00:35:44.300 --> 00:35:47.660
and a performance of a
musical memorial as such--

00:35:47.660 --> 00:35:49.370
a work like the
one we just heard,

00:35:49.370 --> 00:35:52.220
whose subject is
itself commemorative--

00:35:52.220 --> 00:35:57.950
can make for a doubly
strong bridge to the past.

00:35:57.950 --> 00:35:59.840
So that sense of
enlarged temporality

00:35:59.840 --> 00:36:02.000
is one special
attribute of music

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:04.590
I've been trying to get
my mind around this year.

00:36:04.590 --> 00:36:07.130
But let's also quickly
mention a second attribute,

00:36:07.130 --> 00:36:10.460
a certain visceral quality that
I think we would all probably

00:36:10.460 --> 00:36:15.110
agree comes through very clearly
in the example we just heard.

00:36:15.110 --> 00:36:20.150
It's an immediacy that seems
to attend to sound as such.

00:36:20.150 --> 00:36:23.105
It seems connected,
I would think,

00:36:23.105 --> 00:36:25.130
to the nature of hearing.

00:36:25.130 --> 00:36:27.560
The composer Murray
Schafer has written,

00:36:27.560 --> 00:36:32.420
"The eye points outward,
the ear points inward."

00:36:32.420 --> 00:36:35.990
Schafer, who first popularized
the notion of the soundscape,

00:36:35.990 --> 00:36:38.690
which I use in my
title, also reminds us

00:36:38.690 --> 00:36:40.760
that, when we fall
asleep at night,

00:36:40.760 --> 00:36:43.940
it is our hearing that is
the last of the five senses

00:36:43.940 --> 00:36:46.490
to relinquish its guard.

00:36:46.490 --> 00:36:50.360
And it's the first one
to return in the morning.

00:36:50.360 --> 00:36:51.800
In brief, in my
recent work, I've

00:36:51.800 --> 00:36:53.900
been aiming to develop
ways to write and think

00:36:53.900 --> 00:36:56.450
about musical memory that
do justice to these sui

00:36:56.450 --> 00:36:58.490
generis properties
of sound itself,

00:36:58.490 --> 00:37:00.140
and of music as an art form.

00:37:00.140 --> 00:37:03.410
I believe that we can't simply
import wholesale an approach

00:37:03.410 --> 00:37:06.830
from the domains of art
history or visual studies.

00:37:06.830 --> 00:37:09.130
Musical memorials,
I'm arguing here,

00:37:09.130 --> 00:37:11.990
offer the possibility of
a unique, and perhaps more

00:37:11.990 --> 00:37:15.890
immersive, grappling with
the performance of memory

00:37:15.890 --> 00:37:17.720
then and now.

00:37:17.720 --> 00:37:20.750
Adapting from Bakhtin, we can
say they have a special way of,

00:37:20.750 --> 00:37:25.010
quote, "thickening time,
introducing new continuities."

00:37:25.010 --> 00:37:27.000
Under the best conditions,
I am suggesting,

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:30.590
these works can help dispel
what Walter Benjamin described

00:37:30.590 --> 00:37:34.010
as the expanse of homogeneous
empty time separating us

00:37:34.010 --> 00:37:35.360
from the past.

00:37:35.360 --> 00:37:38.090
Instead, musical memory,
works like this one,

00:37:38.090 --> 00:37:41.150
have the potential to bring us
closer to what Benjamin called

00:37:41.150 --> 00:37:44.180
the jetztzeit, or
in his words, "time

00:37:44.180 --> 00:37:46.280
filled by the
presence of the now."

00:37:49.930 --> 00:37:53.440
Speaking of time, in the stretch
that we have remaining together

00:37:53.440 --> 00:37:56.200
today, I'd like to
speak about one more

00:37:56.200 --> 00:37:58.780
score, another instance
of musical memory,

00:37:58.780 --> 00:38:03.110
and then offer some
concluding thoughts.

00:38:03.110 --> 00:38:05.860
In A Survivor from
Warsaw, we've already

00:38:05.860 --> 00:38:08.950
heard a piece that
derives its power,

00:38:08.950 --> 00:38:11.620
it's kind of burning
intensity, in part

00:38:11.620 --> 00:38:13.870
from its composer's
proximity, I think,

00:38:13.870 --> 00:38:16.150
to the history he describes.

00:38:16.150 --> 00:38:18.130
There is a rawness
and a directness

00:38:18.130 --> 00:38:19.990
to that piece of music.

00:38:19.990 --> 00:38:22.360
I'd now like to turn to a
different score that speaks,

00:38:22.360 --> 00:38:25.810
at a certain level, of
temporal and geographic removed

00:38:25.810 --> 00:38:27.160
from the war years.

00:38:27.160 --> 00:38:30.460
In that sense, it addresses
more seamlessly the moment

00:38:30.460 --> 00:38:31.435
we are living in today.

00:38:33.990 --> 00:38:37.680
The American composer, Steve
Reich, was born in 1936

00:38:37.680 --> 00:38:41.580
and grew up in this country,
far from the agonies of Europe.

00:38:41.580 --> 00:38:45.240
As a boy with divorced parents
living on opposite coasts,

00:38:45.240 --> 00:38:48.300
he used to take long
train voyages, accompanied

00:38:48.300 --> 00:38:52.770
by his governess, between
New York and Los Angeles.

00:38:52.770 --> 00:38:56.040
Decades later, as an
adult, in the 1980s,

00:38:56.040 --> 00:39:00.150
he came across the iconic photo
of a frightened boy standing

00:39:00.150 --> 00:39:04.320
on the streets of the Warsaw
ghetto with his hands raised.

00:39:04.320 --> 00:39:09.090
Reich saw in that boy an
image of a kind of alter self.

00:39:09.090 --> 00:39:12.090
He and the boy looked
physically alike, he thought,

00:39:12.090 --> 00:39:13.800
and given the year
of the photo, they

00:39:13.800 --> 00:39:17.310
might well have been
born at the same time.

00:39:17.310 --> 00:39:18.870
They were separated,
Reich realized,

00:39:18.870 --> 00:39:22.920
only by a senseless
accident of fate.

00:39:22.920 --> 00:39:24.780
Had he, Reich, been
born in Europe,

00:39:24.780 --> 00:39:27.330
the trains he rode as
a child, he realized,

00:39:27.330 --> 00:39:29.970
would not be associated
with quaint memories

00:39:29.970 --> 00:39:32.520
of Pullman porters
and of his governess.

00:39:32.520 --> 00:39:37.080
They would have been, in his
phrase, different trains.

00:39:37.080 --> 00:39:39.780
This became the title,
and the framing conceit,

00:39:39.780 --> 00:39:43.200
of Reich's three movement work
for string quartet and tape

00:39:43.200 --> 00:39:45.750
that was premiered in 1988.

00:39:45.750 --> 00:39:47.830
Some of you have surely
heard it performed.

00:39:47.830 --> 00:39:51.270
We'll hear a little bit
of the music in a moment.

00:39:51.270 --> 00:39:54.390
The defining gesture of
Reich's musical score

00:39:54.390 --> 00:39:58.530
is the transfer of
actual survivor voices,

00:39:58.530 --> 00:40:01.980
present through samples that
he took from recorded survivor

00:40:01.980 --> 00:40:07.020
testimony, into the voices of
the instruments of the string

00:40:07.020 --> 00:40:09.330
quartet, which played
lines transcribed

00:40:09.330 --> 00:40:12.210
from the contours
of the spoken words.

00:40:12.210 --> 00:40:17.580
Memory here is, quite
literally, inscribed in sound.

00:40:17.580 --> 00:40:20.047
It may seem as abstract
as I describe it now,

00:40:20.047 --> 00:40:22.380
but we'll see and hear shortly
the technique is actually

00:40:22.380 --> 00:40:24.000
beautifully simple
and, in a way,

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:27.420
this work embodies another set
of themes I've tried to weave

00:40:27.420 --> 00:40:29.400
through this afternoon's talk.

00:40:29.400 --> 00:40:31.500
Different Trains is
music that dances

00:40:31.500 --> 00:40:35.280
in that liminal space between
spoken and the unspoken,

00:40:35.280 --> 00:40:38.160
between the flinty
precision of language

00:40:38.160 --> 00:40:41.250
and the watery
sensuality of sound.

00:40:41.250 --> 00:40:43.500
Throughout this piece,
there is no narrator, only

00:40:43.500 --> 00:40:45.840
shards of disconnected speech--

00:40:45.840 --> 00:40:48.750
tiny slivers of language
that, with a kind

00:40:48.750 --> 00:40:51.900
of metonymic virtuosity,
become all that

00:40:51.900 --> 00:40:54.600
is required at this
late date to summon

00:40:54.600 --> 00:40:57.390
the enormity of the tragedy.

00:40:57.390 --> 00:40:59.010
In this brief
excerpt, we'll hear

00:40:59.010 --> 00:41:03.480
a survivor named Rachella say
a few simple words and phrases.

00:41:03.480 --> 00:41:06.000
"1940," she says.

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:08.880
Then later, "on my birthday."

00:41:08.880 --> 00:41:12.900
Then later again, "the
Germans walked in."

00:41:12.900 --> 00:41:14.640
We will hear a
viola, or at times,

00:41:14.640 --> 00:41:17.550
a cello tracing the rise and
fall of Rachella's voice,

00:41:17.550 --> 00:41:20.130
and then picking up the
resulting melodic line

00:41:20.130 --> 00:41:21.680
shorn of its words.

00:41:21.680 --> 00:41:26.880
We'll also, I will warn you,
hear Reich's use of sirens.

00:41:26.880 --> 00:41:27.720
Let's have a listen.

00:41:27.720 --> 00:41:30.960
Here is the first two minutes
of the second movement

00:41:30.960 --> 00:41:32.449
of Different Trains.

