00:43:17.239 --> 00:43:19.235
A very tall man.

00:43:19.235 --> 00:43:23.227
He said, "Black Crows"--

00:43:23.227 --> 00:43:30.213
"Black Crows"-- He said, "Black
Crows invaded our country."

00:43:30.213 --> 00:43:36.700
He said, "Black Crows invaded
our country many years ago."

00:43:36.700 --> 00:43:38.696
And he pointed right at me.

00:43:38.696 --> 00:43:40.193
He pointed right at me.

00:43:50.769 --> 00:43:52.310
- That was just a
snippet, of course,

00:43:52.310 --> 00:43:55.170
and please believe me, the
work's full power comes through

00:43:55.170 --> 00:43:57.480
much more clearly
as an entirety,

00:43:57.480 --> 00:44:00.420
preferably in a
live performance.

00:44:00.420 --> 00:44:02.520
This was enough, though,
I hope, to give you

00:44:02.520 --> 00:44:06.150
a sense of the ways in
which the score actually

00:44:06.150 --> 00:44:10.950
furnishes more than just a
potent listening experience.

00:44:10.950 --> 00:44:14.100
It also operationalizes,
if we could say,

00:44:14.100 --> 00:44:16.710
a certain store of metaphors.

00:44:16.710 --> 00:44:20.220
By inviting the listener to
reverse engineer his melodies,

00:44:20.220 --> 00:44:23.610
to associate them with the
actual voices that formed

00:44:23.610 --> 00:44:26.320
their contours, the
voices from the era,

00:44:26.320 --> 00:44:28.670
Reich makes
overwhelmingly tactile

00:44:28.670 --> 00:44:31.500
the ways in which the
past is always conferring

00:44:31.500 --> 00:44:33.390
its shape on the present.

00:44:33.390 --> 00:44:37.134
And then, like the
voices, taking its leave.

00:44:37.134 --> 00:44:38.550
At the same time,
this piece wants

00:44:38.550 --> 00:44:41.040
to hold on to the
singularity of those voices,

00:44:41.040 --> 00:44:43.170
those links to actual people.

00:44:43.170 --> 00:44:46.440
I think it is this
documentary specificity that

00:44:46.440 --> 00:44:49.170
helps this score to
avoid the pitfalls of so

00:44:49.170 --> 00:44:51.450
much other memorial art.

00:44:51.450 --> 00:44:54.270
And I'm speaking of the
cinematic re-enactments

00:44:54.270 --> 00:44:59.040
and memory kitsch that I think
can feel pervasive these days,

00:44:59.040 --> 00:45:02.580
and can sometimes threaten
to numb the senses.

00:45:02.580 --> 00:45:04.140
Reich's Different
Trains ultimately

00:45:04.140 --> 00:45:06.210
makes palpable the
ways in which the past

00:45:06.210 --> 00:45:09.690
we are discussing tonight
oscillates between the spoken

00:45:09.690 --> 00:45:11.010
and the unspoken.

00:45:11.010 --> 00:45:14.340
It also, I think, resonates
with our contemporary moment,

00:45:14.340 --> 00:45:18.510
when the actual living memory
of the Holocaust is receding,

00:45:18.510 --> 00:45:21.360
and the generation who
experienced it directly

00:45:21.360 --> 00:45:24.600
continues to fade.

00:45:24.600 --> 00:45:27.930
Like Reich's sampled
voices, their memories

00:45:27.930 --> 00:45:34.020
now leave cultural traces that,
in turn, shape the contours

00:45:34.020 --> 00:45:35.640
and cadences of our own.

00:45:38.450 --> 00:45:41.930
By way of a conclusion, I'd
like to refresh our memories

00:45:41.930 --> 00:45:46.030
about the well-known closing
passage of Adorno's Minima

00:45:46.030 --> 00:45:49.340
Moralia, a book
composed of fragments.

00:45:49.340 --> 00:45:52.970
In this passage,
as I see it, Adorno

00:45:52.970 --> 00:45:54.770
came close to
distilling his life's

00:45:54.770 --> 00:45:57.540
work in a single sentence.

00:45:57.540 --> 00:45:59.990
He wrote that,
quote, "Perspectives

00:45:59.990 --> 00:46:04.150
must be fashioned that displace
and estrange the world,

00:46:04.150 --> 00:46:07.250
reveal it to be, with
its rifts and crevices,

00:46:07.250 --> 00:46:11.570
as indigent and distorted
as it will one day appear

00:46:11.570 --> 00:46:15.060
in the messianic light."

00:46:15.060 --> 00:46:20.460
For Adorno, this, and this
alone, was the task of thought,

00:46:20.460 --> 00:46:23.640
and certainly the task
of critical theory.

00:46:23.640 --> 00:46:25.500
Yet, I believe
Adorno, of all people,

00:46:25.500 --> 00:46:29.280
would forgive us one further
interpolation, that he would,

00:46:29.280 --> 00:46:33.630
in fact, agree that this
self-same mission is also one

00:46:33.630 --> 00:46:36.870
of the essential
tasks of art itself--

00:46:36.870 --> 00:46:39.420
to fashion the
perspectives on the world,

00:46:39.420 --> 00:46:41.010
from which the brokenness--

00:46:41.010 --> 00:46:42.660
the rifts and fissures--

00:46:42.660 --> 00:46:45.600
of the present and the
past are revealed and felt

00:46:45.600 --> 00:46:46.860
for what they are.

00:46:46.860 --> 00:46:49.680
And not only the brokenness
in the past, of course,

00:46:49.680 --> 00:46:53.130
but also its buried sparks
of hope for a future

00:46:53.130 --> 00:46:55.722
that might still have
turned out differently.

00:46:59.100 --> 00:47:01.110
Every modern art
form contributes

00:47:01.110 --> 00:47:03.300
to this task in different ways.

00:47:03.300 --> 00:47:05.730
As I hope I've given you at
least a glimpse of today,

00:47:05.730 --> 00:47:08.370
music has its own
contribution to make.

00:47:08.370 --> 00:47:11.280
For me, at least, it has always
been the best of the arts

00:47:11.280 --> 00:47:15.270
at conveying this expanded
present tense, that sense

00:47:15.270 --> 00:47:18.420
of contact with
history and memory,

00:47:18.420 --> 00:47:21.570
and that basic truth so
elegantly distilled by WG

00:47:21.570 --> 00:47:25.530
Sebald in a deceptively
simple observation.

00:47:25.530 --> 00:47:29.260
He wrote that, quote, "Time
measures nothing but itself."

00:47:29.260 --> 00:47:30.757
Thank you.

00:47:30.757 --> 00:47:33.252
[APPLAUSE]

00:47:39.750 --> 00:47:44.210
- I'm a professor emeritus of
English, of Nichols College,

00:47:44.210 --> 00:47:47.570
and, yes, I've just
been reading a lot

00:47:47.570 --> 00:47:50.270
of Baudelaire's critiques.

00:47:50.270 --> 00:47:55.790
And I noticed that both of the
pieces that you played to us

00:47:55.790 --> 00:47:58.370
have words with them.

00:47:58.370 --> 00:48:01.810
And the Guernica did not have
words associated with it,

00:48:01.810 --> 00:48:03.500
but it was not realism.

00:48:03.500 --> 00:48:10.160
So the imagination
of the listener

00:48:10.160 --> 00:48:13.370
could be set free to imagine.

00:48:13.370 --> 00:48:17.330
And I was wondering
what you think

00:48:17.330 --> 00:48:23.990
about composers like Schoenberg
adding words to his music,

00:48:23.990 --> 00:48:28.040
so that somehow that defines
the memory that you're

00:48:28.040 --> 00:48:32.500
going to have, rather
than opening up

00:48:32.500 --> 00:48:39.760
the listener's memory to
his or her own thoughts?

00:48:39.760 --> 00:48:40.750
- Yeah, absolutely.

00:48:40.750 --> 00:48:41.770
It's a great point.

00:48:41.770 --> 00:48:43.790
We spoke about all
those semantic tricks

00:48:43.790 --> 00:48:45.770
that abstract music
can play, and then I

00:48:45.770 --> 00:48:51.330
went ahead and played you
two excerpts with words.

00:48:51.330 --> 00:48:53.900
The short answer is
that I think there

00:48:53.900 --> 00:48:57.200
are really effective
musical memorials in both

00:48:57.200 --> 00:49:01.270
of those types, both
of those genres.

00:49:01.270 --> 00:49:03.770
In the book project
that I'm working on,

00:49:03.770 --> 00:49:06.350
I hope to spend some
time writing and thinking

00:49:06.350 --> 00:49:08.630
about Strauss'
Metamorphosen, which

00:49:08.630 --> 00:49:12.290
is a strictly instrumental
work that was written shortly

00:49:12.290 --> 00:49:16.460
after the war, and is heard
by many as a kind of memorial

00:49:16.460 --> 00:49:20.480
to the destruction
of German culture.

00:49:20.480 --> 00:49:26.270
And I think that what I tried
to bring out also in the Reich

00:49:26.270 --> 00:49:29.510
was that the words--

00:49:29.510 --> 00:49:32.750
I don't personally feel actually
that the words in the Reich

00:49:32.750 --> 00:49:35.840
really guide us into any
particular narrative,

00:49:35.840 --> 00:49:39.800
because they don't
actually tell the story.

00:49:39.800 --> 00:49:43.610
But what they do do,
as I was trying to say,

00:49:43.610 --> 00:49:49.430
was that they anchor the piece
in the actual documentary

00:49:49.430 --> 00:49:52.580
details, the actual
voices of the people

00:49:52.580 --> 00:49:55.010
who lived through that
era, and, at the same time,

00:49:55.010 --> 00:49:58.730
abstract from them
with the musical lines

00:49:58.730 --> 00:50:02.150
that he derives
from their voices.

00:50:02.150 --> 00:50:06.710
And so I think,
in that way, it's

00:50:06.710 --> 00:50:09.890
a perfect memorial for this
particular moment, when

00:50:09.890 --> 00:50:13.010
we are right there on the
threshold between what

00:50:13.010 --> 00:50:15.440
sometimes gets called
communicative memory,

00:50:15.440 --> 00:50:19.400
or talking, telling stories,
and cultural memory,

00:50:19.400 --> 00:50:22.892
preserved through
art and other things.

00:50:22.892 --> 00:50:24.790
Yeah?

00:50:24.790 --> 00:50:25.840
- Hi.

00:50:25.840 --> 00:50:30.760
My name's Julie [INAUDIBLE],
and your discussion

00:50:30.760 --> 00:50:33.310
of Different Trains
threw me back

00:50:33.310 --> 00:50:36.880
into my own musical memory.

00:50:36.880 --> 00:50:41.620
I was at the performance that
the Kronos Quartet did here

00:50:41.620 --> 00:50:44.740
in Cambridge when they
were first touring it.

00:50:44.740 --> 00:50:46.810
I was in my late 20s.

00:50:46.810 --> 00:50:50.140
I was a composition student,
with a group of friends,

00:50:50.140 --> 00:50:52.660
who were not
professional musicians,

00:50:52.660 --> 00:50:56.230
but we all went and did lots of
cool cultural stuff together.

00:50:56.230 --> 00:50:58.960
And all of my
friends were Jewish.

00:50:58.960 --> 00:51:01.420
And two of them-- although I
didn't know it at the time--

00:51:01.420 --> 00:51:04.030
were children of survivors.

00:51:04.030 --> 00:51:05.890
We didn't know what
was on the program,

00:51:05.890 --> 00:51:10.330
and so this piece came as
a surprise to everyone.

00:51:10.330 --> 00:51:12.430
Being a composer, I was
very focused on what

00:51:12.430 --> 00:51:14.740
he was doing with the
tape and the rhythm,

00:51:14.740 --> 00:51:16.600
and all that kind of stuff.

00:51:16.600 --> 00:51:20.860
And we had, I think, one
of the longest and most

00:51:20.860 --> 00:51:24.520
passionate discussions after
this concert among my friends

00:51:24.520 --> 00:51:27.010
I experienced with that group.

00:51:27.010 --> 00:51:29.650
And looking back,
my two friends,

00:51:29.650 --> 00:51:32.830
whose parents had
survived the camps,

00:51:32.830 --> 00:51:36.610
were the ones who were most
angry about this piece.

00:51:36.610 --> 00:51:38.920
They found it utterly insulting.

00:51:38.920 --> 00:51:41.260
They found it trivializing,
and they hated

00:51:41.260 --> 00:51:43.780
the fragmentation of the text.

00:51:43.780 --> 00:51:47.110
And just now, it
was making me wonder

00:51:47.110 --> 00:51:52.750
about the space between
memorializing and experiencing.

00:51:52.750 --> 00:51:55.230
And I wondered if you might
say a little about that?

00:51:58.580 --> 00:52:00.800
- It's a great question,
and that's a big subject,

00:52:00.800 --> 00:52:02.880
of course.

00:52:02.880 --> 00:52:10.040
I quoted from Adorno's very
affirmative embrace of Survivor

00:52:10.040 --> 00:52:14.240
from Warsaw as a
piece that reflected

00:52:14.240 --> 00:52:16.700
and incorporated the
barbarism of the times

00:52:16.700 --> 00:52:21.460
into the frame of the artwork,
like Picasso's Guernica.

00:52:21.460 --> 00:52:23.930
What I didn't quote from is
some of the later opinions

00:52:23.930 --> 00:52:25.460
he had of the work.

00:52:25.460 --> 00:52:29.720
He was around for long enough
after the war to reconsider his

00:52:29.720 --> 00:52:35.560
opinions, and wrote, really
interestingly, in the 1960s,

00:52:35.560 --> 00:52:38.780
a kind of second thoughts
on Survivor from Warsaw,

00:52:38.780 --> 00:52:43.220
and spoke in particular about
a certain operea, he called it,

00:52:43.220 --> 00:52:52.710
that exists in Survivor from
Warsaw between acknowledging

00:52:52.710 --> 00:52:55.130
the victims of the
Holocaust-- the barbarism,

00:52:55.130 --> 00:52:57.440
the violence that
was done to them--

00:52:57.440 --> 00:53:03.680
on the one hand, but also being
careful not to instrumentalize

00:53:03.680 --> 00:53:08.960
their memories, to use them
for the purpose of somehow

00:53:08.960 --> 00:53:13.730
possibly entertaining an
audience, or giving them

00:53:13.730 --> 00:53:14.582
pleasure.

00:53:14.582 --> 00:53:16.290
Because of course, at
the end of the day,

00:53:16.290 --> 00:53:19.670
this was a tragedy for which
there is no redemption.

00:53:19.670 --> 00:53:21.320
There was only death.

00:53:21.320 --> 00:53:24.920
And so this question
he raises of--

00:53:24.920 --> 00:53:26.360
he says something
along the lines

00:53:26.360 --> 00:53:29.180
that, no work of art that
ignores the victims can

00:53:29.180 --> 00:53:33.920
possibly be of credit, or
of value, in this context,

00:53:33.920 --> 00:53:38.330
and at the same time, no work
of art that that exploits

00:53:38.330 --> 00:53:43.850
their memories should be
allowed to stand as well.

00:53:43.850 --> 00:53:47.720
So for him, that was the operea
in which all memory art stands.

00:53:47.720 --> 00:53:51.620
And I do think of that as
a kind of guiding framework

00:53:51.620 --> 00:53:54.650
for thinking about all of
our writing and responses

00:53:54.650 --> 00:53:57.080
and engagement with these works.

00:53:57.080 --> 00:54:00.380
I think that, for
different people,

00:54:00.380 --> 00:54:02.000
they will draw that
line differently,

00:54:02.000 --> 00:54:06.110
and even the line perhaps seems
different at different points

00:54:06.110 --> 00:54:08.080
of remove from when
the work was written,

00:54:08.080 --> 00:54:10.349
and as we ourselves
change and grow older.

00:54:10.349 --> 00:54:12.140
I would wonder what
your friends might feel

00:54:12.140 --> 00:54:14.370
about Different Trains now.

00:54:14.370 --> 00:54:16.840
But I think those are
some very good points.

00:54:16.840 --> 00:54:20.150
Thank you for your comment.

00:54:20.150 --> 00:54:20.930
- I'm Dan Wikler.

00:54:20.930 --> 00:54:22.888
I'm a professor at the
School of Public Health,

00:54:22.888 --> 00:54:26.990
and I have a brief observation,
and then a question.

00:54:26.990 --> 00:54:30.820
Many years ago, I read
Perfect Pitch, a memoir

00:54:30.820 --> 00:54:35.390
by a musical lexicographer,
Nicholas Slonimsky.

00:54:35.390 --> 00:54:38.900
And I believe he said
in there, at one point,

00:54:38.900 --> 00:54:41.630
he had been close
to Koussevitzky,

00:54:41.630 --> 00:54:46.040
who then suddenly turned on
him and sort of dismissed him.

00:54:46.040 --> 00:54:47.650
And it hurt his
feelings terribly.

00:54:47.650 --> 00:54:53.300
And if I remember right, his
wife, as she threw him out

00:54:53.300 --> 00:54:55.460
of their living
room, said, you're

00:54:55.460 --> 00:54:58.220
nothing but a cheap, Odessa Jew.

00:54:58.220 --> 00:55:02.550
And Slonimsky's thought to
himself, as he walked away,

00:55:02.550 --> 00:55:06.050
but Koussevitzky's
an Odessa Jew, too.

00:55:06.050 --> 00:55:08.480
And I know that
Koussevitzky had converted

00:55:08.480 --> 00:55:12.260
to Christianity, either as a
teenager or as a young man,

00:55:12.260 --> 00:55:15.540
and was buried in a
Christian graveyard,

00:55:15.540 --> 00:55:17.540
and I wonder if there's
some problems there

00:55:17.540 --> 00:55:21.960
that might help to explain why
he didn't play the Schoenberg.

00:55:21.960 --> 00:55:23.550
The question is this--

00:55:23.550 --> 00:55:28.340
you mentioned Resnais'
movie, Night and Fog,

00:55:28.340 --> 00:55:30.650
which I've seen more
times than I can count.

00:55:33.359 --> 00:55:35.400
One striking thing about
that movie is the score.

00:55:35.400 --> 00:55:37.710
It's by Hanns Eisler.

00:55:37.710 --> 00:55:41.590
And when I first heard
the score, I thought,

00:55:41.590 --> 00:55:43.520
this is wildly inappropriate.

00:55:43.520 --> 00:55:46.960
It's not a dirge,
or it's not even--

00:55:46.960 --> 00:55:48.780
It doesn't sound sad.

00:55:48.780 --> 00:55:53.520
It's a kind of
almost perky score.

00:55:53.520 --> 00:55:56.570
It's mood changes
from moment to moment.

00:55:56.570 --> 00:56:00.680
But if I heard that
thing in a concert,

00:56:00.680 --> 00:56:04.490
without being told that it
was written for Night and Fog,

00:56:04.490 --> 00:56:06.320
I would never have dreamed it.

00:56:06.320 --> 00:56:09.530
But over time, as I've watched
that film over and over,

00:56:09.530 --> 00:56:11.890
and heard that music,
it's come, to me,

00:56:11.890 --> 00:56:15.290
to seem the absolutely
perfect music for that movie.

00:56:15.290 --> 00:56:19.490
And I almost can't imagine
the movie without it.

00:56:19.490 --> 00:56:21.950
And I don't know whether
it's my brain making this up,

00:56:21.950 --> 00:56:23.870
or whether there's
something in the music

00:56:23.870 --> 00:56:29.240
that he somehow had figured out,
despite the fact that it seems

00:56:29.240 --> 00:56:30.800
so completely different in tone.

00:56:30.800 --> 00:56:34.810
And I wondered if you
have any thoughts on that?

00:56:34.810 --> 00:56:35.490
- Yeah.

00:56:35.490 --> 00:56:41.550
So Hanns Eisler, the
composer of that score,

00:56:41.550 --> 00:56:45.570
was a student of
Arnold Schoenberg's.

00:56:45.570 --> 00:56:48.870
After A Survivor from
Warsaw was written,

00:56:48.870 --> 00:56:53.580
Eisler had comments
in a lecture,

00:56:53.580 --> 00:56:56.310
or a published
article, in which he

00:56:56.310 --> 00:57:01.740
said that Schoenberg was
the quintessential composer

00:57:01.740 --> 00:57:06.450
of fear, and that his
genius was in the fact

00:57:06.450 --> 00:57:13.140
that he understood the
meaning of aerial bombardment

00:57:13.140 --> 00:57:14.940
and the meaning of
the gas chambers

00:57:14.940 --> 00:57:18.240
back at a time when
the world was still

00:57:18.240 --> 00:57:20.700
safe for the man in the street.

00:57:20.700 --> 00:57:27.900
So Eisler, I think, had a very
apt sense, and sharp sense,

00:57:27.900 --> 00:57:30.660
of what Schoenberg
was trying to do.

00:57:34.001 --> 00:57:34.500
As

00:57:34.500 --> 00:57:36.583
As for that film, I mean,
I think it's interesting

00:57:36.583 --> 00:57:38.850
that familiarity
sometimes breeds contempt,

00:57:38.850 --> 00:57:43.890
and also, of course, sometimes
love when it comes to music.

00:57:43.890 --> 00:57:47.340
I thought also, during
your comment, about some

00:57:47.340 --> 00:57:50.310
of the ideas Philip
Glass sometimes brings up

00:57:50.310 --> 00:57:52.510
when he talks about
his own film music,

00:57:52.510 --> 00:58:00.030
and the idea of a score's
purpose as not to necessarily

00:58:00.030 --> 00:58:05.790
create an auditory analog,
a sonic kind of mirror,

00:58:05.790 --> 00:58:08.190
to the action that you're
seeing in the film,

00:58:08.190 --> 00:58:10.860
but rather to open
up a sense of space,

00:58:10.860 --> 00:58:15.150
almost a sense of
distance, between the music

00:58:15.150 --> 00:58:18.090
and the action within
which we, as viewers,

00:58:18.090 --> 00:58:22.590
or the individual self, can
appreciate what's being offered

00:58:22.590 --> 00:58:24.870
to maximum effect.

00:58:24.870 --> 00:58:28.170
Obviously, Eisler had not
read Philip Glass when doing--

00:58:28.170 --> 00:58:31.740
and Philip Glass had
written those things yet.

00:58:31.740 --> 00:58:34.510
But those are a few thoughts
in responses to your comment.

00:58:34.510 --> 00:58:36.290
Thank you.

00:58:36.290 --> 00:58:36.790
- Thank you.

00:58:36.790 --> 00:58:37.540
Hello.

00:58:37.540 --> 00:58:38.640
I'm Aleksandra Kremer.

00:58:38.640 --> 00:58:40.700
I'm an assistant
professor of Polish

00:58:40.700 --> 00:58:43.030
from the Slavic Department
here at Harvard.

00:58:43.030 --> 00:58:45.150
And I have like a very
short commentary, which

00:58:45.150 --> 00:58:47.020
will lead me to my question.

00:58:47.020 --> 00:58:51.300
And so thank you
for your great talk.

00:58:51.300 --> 00:58:53.130
Well, from the
American perspective,

00:58:53.130 --> 00:58:55.140
and also from the
perspective of music,

00:58:55.140 --> 00:58:58.590
certainly Schoenberg's work
is like a very early response,

00:58:58.590 --> 00:59:00.030
very quick response.

00:59:00.030 --> 00:59:04.890
It made me very quickly to think
also about earlier artistic

00:59:04.890 --> 00:59:08.910
responses to
Holocaust, and to war,

00:59:08.910 --> 00:59:11.640
which appeared especially
in Polish culture, like,

00:59:11.640 --> 00:59:15.300
for example, Czeslaw Milosz,
who lived in the occupied Warsaw

00:59:15.300 --> 00:59:17.250
exactly at the time of
the ghetto uprising,

00:59:17.250 --> 00:59:20.220
and wrote two of his important
poems in '43 already--

00:59:20.220 --> 00:59:23.640
A Poor Christian Looks at the
Ghetto and Campo dei Fiori.

00:59:23.640 --> 00:59:27.330
I think also of Zofia Nalkowska,
whose book, Medallions,

00:59:27.330 --> 00:59:30.430
responses to exactly
the Nazis crimes.

00:59:30.430 --> 00:59:33.460
And I think of Tadeusz
Borowsky, translated as,

00:59:33.460 --> 00:59:35.430
This Way for the Gas,
Ladies and Gentlemen.

00:59:35.430 --> 00:59:37.130
This was '46 already.

00:59:37.130 --> 00:59:38.970
And these were all
like radical revisions

00:59:38.970 --> 00:59:41.130
of what literature can be.

00:59:41.130 --> 00:59:43.510
And also, in terms
of memorialization,

00:59:43.510 --> 00:59:46.620
like the first tablet
honoring the heroes

00:59:46.620 --> 00:59:48.245
of the ghetto
uprising in Warsaw.

00:59:48.245 --> 00:59:51.660
In Warsaw, it was '46,
and the monument's '48.

00:59:51.660 --> 00:59:53.850
So it's like, from
European perspective,

00:59:53.850 --> 00:59:56.645
it's not that
early, even in '47.

00:59:56.645 --> 00:59:58.020
And this leads me
to a question--

00:59:58.020 --> 01:00:00.330
to what extent, really,
the soundscape, which

01:00:00.330 --> 01:00:04.890
you have in your title, are
best conveyed via music,

01:00:04.890 --> 01:00:07.190
and not, for example,
like literature,

01:00:07.190 --> 01:00:10.200
as the soundscape also
consists of so many words

01:00:10.200 --> 01:00:11.520
and exclamations.

01:00:11.520 --> 01:00:14.910
And also, when I think
about theater and cinema,

01:00:14.910 --> 01:00:18.030
to what extent really
full soundscape can

01:00:18.030 --> 01:00:21.510
be best preserved in
the work of musical art,

01:00:21.510 --> 01:00:25.050
which is still not that radical,
in terms of experimentation,

01:00:25.050 --> 01:00:26.490
at least what we have here.

01:00:26.490 --> 01:00:30.300
And do you have any thoughts,
like a rivalry of these words,

01:00:30.300 --> 01:00:33.944
literature and music, in
terms of memorialization,

01:00:33.944 --> 01:00:36.360
because you mostly talked about
visual arts and monuments?

01:00:36.360 --> 01:00:38.362
And I would like to
thank you so much.

01:00:38.362 --> 01:00:39.660
- Yeah.

01:00:39.660 --> 01:00:40.860
Thank you for the question.

01:00:40.860 --> 01:00:45.420
And I would never like
to think about a rivalry

01:00:45.420 --> 01:00:49.410
between literature and
music, as regards memory art.

01:00:49.410 --> 01:00:52.110
And I would hope that we
wouldn't have to choose.

01:00:52.110 --> 01:00:54.930
It does seem like, in
my own work with some

01:00:54.930 --> 01:00:58.230
of these pieces, and
generally as a critic,

01:00:58.230 --> 01:01:03.450
I've often tried to read
music and literature, or music

01:01:03.450 --> 01:01:06.960
and other arts, in the
image of each other,

01:01:06.960 --> 01:01:10.170
as a helpful way to write and
to think, and to make sense

01:01:10.170 --> 01:01:13.920
of what was being done by these
artists who were all breathing

01:01:13.920 --> 01:01:14.770
the same air.

01:01:18.910 --> 01:01:22.540
The idea of the
soundscape in the title,

01:01:22.540 --> 01:01:24.460
again, comes from
Murray Schafer.

01:01:24.460 --> 01:01:27.460
And I hadn't been
thinking about it

01:01:27.460 --> 01:01:31.360
as kind of having anyone
appointed to sort of check

01:01:31.360 --> 01:01:36.760
the passport of the art form at
the border, if you understand.

01:01:36.760 --> 01:01:41.040
I would be happy to think
more about literature's place

01:01:41.040 --> 01:01:42.370
in the soundscape.

01:01:42.370 --> 01:01:45.400
For me, it was just
a way of distilling

01:01:45.400 --> 01:01:49.570
this idea of auditory
memory, and of getting

01:01:49.570 --> 01:01:55.700
at some of these issues
of sound specificity.

01:01:55.700 --> 01:01:58.270
I have in my work already
written a whole chapter

01:01:58.270 --> 01:02:02.170
on the way stone monuments
differ from monuments in sound.

01:02:02.170 --> 01:02:04.600
And it's a great
idea, perhaps it

01:02:04.600 --> 01:02:07.510
would be really helpful and
instructive, to think through,

01:02:07.510 --> 01:02:10.780
in a systematic
way, how memorials

01:02:10.780 --> 01:02:13.330
in literature and
words also might

01:02:13.330 --> 01:02:15.130
differ from memorials in sound.

01:02:15.130 --> 01:02:18.570
Thank you for your comment.

01:02:18.570 --> 01:02:20.380
- My name is Donald Tipper.

01:02:20.380 --> 01:02:22.320
I'm a retired professor
at the University

01:02:22.320 --> 01:02:24.780
of Massachusetts Medical School.

01:02:24.780 --> 01:02:28.230
And I had a question
relating to a somewhat more

01:02:28.230 --> 01:02:30.990
universal consequence
of warfare,

01:02:30.990 --> 01:02:33.890
and that is the
effect on children.

01:02:33.890 --> 01:02:36.440
That happens wherever
it is, whatever

01:02:36.440 --> 01:02:42.330
country, the young always
those who suffer terribly.

01:02:42.330 --> 01:02:44.520
I was four years old
when war was declared

01:02:44.520 --> 01:02:47.250
in the United Kingdom
in 1939, and I

01:02:47.250 --> 01:02:49.530
can remember it very well.

01:02:49.530 --> 01:02:52.680
But there are certain things
that bring back memories.

01:02:52.680 --> 01:02:58.530
Of course, odors are the most
direct things that bring back

01:02:58.530 --> 01:03:00.460
memories to almost everybody.

01:03:00.460 --> 01:03:03.130
But sound is probably next.

01:03:03.130 --> 01:03:06.360
And for a child who lived in a
country which was not invaded,

01:03:06.360 --> 01:03:12.405
but which was bombarded, the
sound that is most provocative

01:03:12.405 --> 01:03:15.760
is the sound of the
air raid warning sound.

01:03:15.760 --> 01:03:18.010
Just a siren going up and down.

01:03:18.010 --> 01:03:19.810
That was actually
part of the background

01:03:19.810 --> 01:03:23.080
music in the Koussevitzky,
I think it was.

01:03:23.080 --> 01:03:26.680
And I'm surprised that there
are not more references

01:03:26.680 --> 01:03:30.010
to that kind of
influence of sound

01:03:30.010 --> 01:03:32.590
within the music
that tries to reflect

01:03:32.590 --> 01:03:35.650
the experiences of warfare.

01:03:35.650 --> 01:03:38.110
Of course, explosions
and that sort of thing,

01:03:38.110 --> 01:03:40.240
everybody can expect that.

01:03:40.240 --> 01:03:45.830
But something that has more to
do with everybody's experience.

01:03:45.830 --> 01:03:49.340
Because not
everybody is directly

01:03:49.340 --> 01:03:53.930
affected by such events,
but the fear is universal.

01:03:57.182 --> 01:03:58.890
I don't know what you
can say about that,

01:03:58.890 --> 01:04:02.915
but I just thought it
was worth discussing.

01:04:02.915 --> 01:04:04.290
- Thank you for
your observation.

01:04:04.290 --> 01:04:06.507
There were so many
musical memorials

01:04:06.507 --> 01:04:08.340
I didn't get to speak
about today because we

01:04:08.340 --> 01:04:10.060
had a short amount of time.

01:04:10.060 --> 01:04:12.420
One of them, of course,
is Britten's War Requiem,

01:04:12.420 --> 01:04:14.910
which was written in
response to the 1940

01:04:14.910 --> 01:04:19.260
bombing of the Coventry
Cathedral in the UK.

01:04:19.260 --> 01:04:24.930
And incidentally, the Nazi code
name for that bombing operation

01:04:24.930 --> 01:04:25.905
was Moonlight Sonata.

01:04:31.590 --> 01:04:34.620
There are other memorials,
not necessarily the Britten,

01:04:34.620 --> 01:04:35.940
but other ones.

01:04:35.940 --> 01:04:41.130
For example, there's a piece
written, called Threnody

01:04:41.130 --> 01:04:43.350
for the Victims of Hiroshima.

01:04:43.350 --> 01:04:46.050
There are all kinds
of memorials that

01:04:46.050 --> 01:04:48.480
do try to take a more
naturalistic approach

01:04:48.480 --> 01:04:53.890
to depicting what is the actual
auditory landscape, soundscape

01:04:53.890 --> 01:04:56.130
of war.

01:04:56.130 --> 01:04:58.320
You know, samples
and other things.

01:04:58.320 --> 01:05:01.970
I think it gets us back
into some thorny territory.

01:05:05.250 --> 01:05:08.640
Is that kind of
direct literalness,

01:05:08.640 --> 01:05:12.531
if you will-- transcribing
the wartime acoustic-- is

01:05:12.531 --> 01:05:14.280
that going to be the
most effective medium

01:05:14.280 --> 01:05:15.795
of commemoration?

01:05:15.795 --> 01:05:18.780
Or is there something
reductive in that,

01:05:18.780 --> 01:05:23.190
and will some people find more
powerful these other works that

01:05:23.190 --> 01:05:25.530
are trying, in different
kinds of evocative language

01:05:25.530 --> 01:05:28.430
and with texts, to maybe
get to a similar place?

01:05:28.430 --> 01:05:30.200
But it's a really good point.

01:05:30.200 --> 01:05:32.610
And it reminds me
to emphasize to you

01:05:32.610 --> 01:05:37.020
all just how we've got to hear
obviously a very small range

01:05:37.020 --> 01:05:38.458
of musical memorials today.

01:05:43.840 --> 01:05:45.410
- I'm Daniel Stepner.

01:05:45.410 --> 01:05:48.110
I'm a musician.

01:05:48.110 --> 01:05:50.930
So many references came up.

01:05:50.930 --> 01:05:51.830
So many things.

01:05:51.830 --> 01:05:54.620
Just to mention a few,
[INAUDIBLE] seems to me

01:05:54.620 --> 01:06:00.770
a memorial of European culture
before the First World War.

01:06:00.770 --> 01:06:01.810
Very interesting.

01:06:01.810 --> 01:06:07.110
Also, Charles Ives'
song, They Are There.

01:06:10.490 --> 01:06:15.200
There's a recording you can find
online, I'm sure, now of Ives

01:06:15.200 --> 01:06:17.330
himself singing this,
and playing piano

01:06:17.330 --> 01:06:20.720
while he's singing, and it is
full of such incredible energy

01:06:20.720 --> 01:06:26.870
and rage at Hitler, basically.

01:06:26.870 --> 01:06:29.400
It was recorded during the
war, but it's worth hearing,

01:06:29.400 --> 01:06:29.900
I think.

01:06:29.900 --> 01:06:32.510
An important document.

01:06:32.510 --> 01:06:37.700
But I guess my question,
Jeremy, is based on a lecture

01:06:37.700 --> 01:06:41.960
I heard you do last year
at Brandeis, and that is,

01:06:41.960 --> 01:06:47.810
linking Survivor from Warsaw
to Schoenberg's opera, Moses

01:06:47.810 --> 01:06:52.651
and Aaron, do you care to
talk about that a little bit?

01:06:52.651 --> 01:06:53.150
- Sure.

01:06:53.150 --> 01:06:54.650
That's great.

01:06:54.650 --> 01:06:56.890
Thank you.

01:06:56.890 --> 01:06:59.510
So I have written--

01:06:59.510 --> 01:07:03.120
it's strange to say, but
I have written a full page

01:07:03.120 --> 01:07:07.160
manuscript about those seven
minutes of music that we heard.

01:07:07.160 --> 01:07:15.410
And one aspect of what Mr.
Stepner is referring to

01:07:15.410 --> 01:07:17.330
is that I spend a
lot of time talking

01:07:17.330 --> 01:07:20.360
about Schoenberg's opera,
Moses and Aaron, which

01:07:20.360 --> 01:07:23.510
was the last major work he
completed while still living

01:07:23.510 --> 01:07:27.730
in Germany, before fleeing
to the United States.

01:07:27.730 --> 01:07:29.870
It's a biblically-themed opera.

01:07:29.870 --> 01:07:32.990
It has two acts
that were written,

01:07:32.990 --> 01:07:34.880
and a third that
was never completed.

01:07:37.610 --> 01:07:40.280
There is a lot to
say about that,

01:07:40.280 --> 01:07:42.710
and we're basically out
of time, so I'm just

01:07:42.710 --> 01:07:45.290
going to try to distill
a kernel or two.

01:07:45.290 --> 01:07:50.780
I think it was Schoenberg's
daughter, Nuria,

01:07:50.780 --> 01:07:54.800
who first referenced in passing
this idea that perhaps Survivor

01:07:54.800 --> 01:07:58.820
from Warsaw should be thought
of as the third act of Moses

01:07:58.820 --> 01:08:00.620
and Aaron.

01:08:00.620 --> 01:08:06.620
And this is, I found, a very
provocative and suggestive line

01:08:06.620 --> 01:08:08.330
of thinking, And
one that I ended up

01:08:08.330 --> 01:08:12.680
picking up in that longer
work and drawing out

01:08:12.680 --> 01:08:14.300
a lot of these connections.

01:08:14.300 --> 01:08:20.270
I think that the reason that
Schoenberg could not complete

01:08:20.270 --> 01:08:24.109
Moses and Aaron-- and this
is my own personal theory--

01:08:24.109 --> 01:08:29.779
is that the work itself was
this kind of final Herculean

01:08:29.779 --> 01:08:35.479
attempt to hold in tension,
and really to reconcile,

01:08:35.479 --> 01:08:38.750
these forces of
Jewishness and Germanness

01:08:38.750 --> 01:08:43.040
that were so definitive for him
over the course of his life up

01:08:43.040 --> 01:08:44.660
to that point.

01:08:44.660 --> 01:08:48.080
And of course, when he tried
to return to the work in exile,

01:08:48.080 --> 01:08:51.120
the very idea of that
reconciliation of Germanness

01:08:51.120 --> 01:08:55.340
and Jewishness had itself
been sort of, we can say,

01:08:55.340 --> 01:08:57.640
I guess, shipwrecked by history.

01:09:00.170 --> 01:09:02.420
So there's a lot of connection
between Moses and Aaron

01:09:02.420 --> 01:09:05.550
and Survivor, and it would be
fun to talk about that with you

01:09:05.550 --> 01:09:06.480
all some other time.

01:09:06.480 --> 01:09:07.680
Thank you.

01:09:07.680 --> 01:09:09.180
[APPLAUSE]

01:09:09.180 --> 01:09:11.930
